Prediction of payment on real credit risk dataset using KNN, decision trees, random forests, bagging and gradient boosting for best model comparison

Nicola Rosca

2024-01-19

Introduction

This report is done by Nicola Rosca alone. It represents the use of various models to predict a credit card defaulting. The response was binary, where 0 was represented by No and 1 was Yes.

The data set provided had 23 variables that are computed in all models. Throughout the coursework, the Y variable has been renamed as Pay.result and mutated into a factor.

The remaining variables represented amount of credit given, gender, education, marital status, age, history of past payments, and bill statements.

The data was already split into a train and a test set, however the train set was further split into validation set.

The aim of this coursework is to identify the best model for a classification problem, where the focus is on the accuracy, sensitivity and specificity of each model.

This analysis can be further used for the medical and environmental industries, as well as business.

Methodology

The first part of this coursework represented the exploratory data analysis, data pre-processing and normalization.

The models used in this coursework, are k-Nearest Neighbor, Decision Trees, Random Forests, Bagging and Gradient Boosting.

K-Nearest Neighbor

k-Nearest Neighbor is a non-parametric method, because it does not assume a parametric form for f(x) and therefore tends to be more flexible in understanding trend data (James et al., 2022). In simpler words, KNN is an algorithm where each observation is predicted based on its similarity to other observation (James et al., 2022). KNN is a memory-based algorithm and uses the caret package. For classification, KNN looks at the most common class based on the given k. In order to be able to use KNN on the given sets, I normalized all three data sets through a normalization function.

KNN is very sensible to the k, and most times the results show that a low k over fits the data and large k under fits. The indication is that for KNN for classification, it is best to assess odd numbers for k, to avoid ties. In this report, I experimented with both types of numbers, and k=3 resulted in the best model fit. This might seem to go contrary to the information reported by B.B.& B. (2020), however it shows that a smaller k=3 is based used for little irrelevant data.

Decision Trees

Tree-based models are algorithms that break the feature space into smaller regions using splitting rules. According to HANDS ON MACHINE LEARNING WITH R, predictions are done using a divide and conquer formula, where data is split into tree diagrams. They are not necessarily used for predictions, but more for variable selection. In this coursework, the decision trees performed show that X6 (payment in September) is a dominant variable with a binary response (or a root node with only two branches). However, when removed from the formula, the tree showed multiple branches and nodes that are used, which also allowed pruning, an action that could not be performed when using X6. (B.B.& B., 2020)

According to HANDS ON MACHINE LEARNING WITH R, a basic decision tree partitions the training data into groups with similar response values and then fits a simple constant in each subgroup. In the case of our classification problem, the possibilities predicted with the decision tree models, have used a part of each within the subgroups. The visualizations show that if unpruned, the general tree that included all the variables was severely overfitting (the labels and leaves were overlapping, regardless of panel and text size). Therefore, I pruned the tree that included all possible variables, including X6, through multiple hyper parameters. Pruning is defined as growing an overly complex tree and then using hyper parameters to find an optimal sub tree. (B.B.& B., 2020)

The one I found was trimmed down using the cp (complexity parameter), min split (minimum split) and max depth hyper parameters (maximum depth). Cutting down branches using this pruning technique found the perfect balance where a model captured the trend or patterns in data, but did not consider the noise data. (B.B.& B., 2020)

Bagging

Bagging is an aggregation of bootstrap samples, which draws samples with the replacement of the initial train data. Bagging helps minimize overfitting, as it is designed to improve stability and accuracy in a classification problem. (B.B.& B., 2020)

In Bagging, b bootstrap samples of the train_data (training data set used in this coursework) are created and used with the classification algorithm, in this case called base learner. The algorithm is applied to each bootstrap sample and the predictions are reported using the plurality vote or by averaging the estimated class probabilities.

According to B.B.& B. (2020), the idea of bagging is also known as the wisdom of the crowd, and essentially means that the aggregation of information in large diverse groups results in decisions that are often better than could have been made by any single member of the group. The more diverse the group members are then the more diverse their perspectives and predictions will be, which often leads to better aggregated information.

Random Forests

Random forests algorithms use the same principles as decision trees. It builds many trees on bootstrapped samples of the train_data. The reason random forests are quite popular is that their output is out-of-the-box, meaning the default values tend to produce good results. In comparison to other machine learning algorithms, they have the least variability in accuracy when tuned. (B.B.& B., 2020)

The rule of sampling for random forests is that 100% of the train_data is observed and replicated in the samples. However, the downside of these models is that they are computationally inefficient, resulting in a loss of time depending on the data and parameters used. In the example of this coursework, running the default random forests algorithms took roughly 5 minutes per model. (B.B.& B., 2020)

Gradient boosting

Gradient boosting models have been proven successful across many industries, because build an ensemble of shallow trees in sequence with each tree learning and improving on the previous one. According to HANDS ON MACHINE LEARNING WITH R (2020), GBMs are considered gradient descent algorithms, which are generic optimization algorithms that find the best solutions for multiple issues.

Gradient boosting combines predictions from weak learners, and improves their performance by updating the weights based one errors from previous iterations, until the model accuracy is improved. (A. and Vidhya, 2024)

Grid search functions // Decision trees, random forests & gradient boosting

In this coursework, I chose to apply a grid search function for all of the above algorithm, in order to be able to identify the best model, based on a series of parameters. (R. and Vidhya, 2023)

Grid searches are used to identify the best hyper parameters values to get the correct predictions without having to apply a manual search method. Grid search uses a different combination of all the specified hyper parameters and their values and calculates the performance for each combination and selects the best value for the hyper parameters. This makes the processing time-consuming and expensive based on the number of hyper parameters involved. (R. and Vidhya, 2023)

Variable selection

The variable selection in this coursework was performed through the computation of the p value and an ols model, used to find the best combination of variables for prediction.

Models

KNN

In order to obtain the best k value, I computed a function that runs knn models and identifies the best k for the highest accuracy. According to the graph below, the best k is the lowest one, where the highest k can cause overfitting or would not be able to find trends in data.

k_values <- 1:20 
accuracies <- sapply(k_values, function(k) {
  model <- knn(train = train_normalised, test = val_normalised, cl = train_labels, k = k)
  mean(model == val_normalised$Pay.result)
})

accuracy_data <- data.frame(k = k_values, Accuracy = accuracies)

ggplot(accuracy_data, aes(x = k, y = Accuracy)) +
  geom_line(color = "orange") +  
  geom_point(color = "purple") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  ggtitle("Accuracy vs. k Value for kNN Model") +
  xlab("k Value") +
  ylab("Accuracy")

Decision trees

The journey of the decision trees in this coursework has been interesting. I have computed a first decision tree with all of the variables available.

dt_withX6 <- rpart(
  Pay.result ~ Credit.value + X2 + X3 + X4 + X5 + X6+  X7 + X8 + X9 + X11 + X12 + X13 + X14 + X15 + X16 + X17 + X18 + X19 + X20 + X21 + X22 + X23,
  data = train_data,
  method = "class"
)

#plot(decisiontree1C,main="decision tree 1C")
#text(decisiontree1C)

par(mar = c(5, 4, 4, 2) + 0.1)

rpart.plot(dt_withX6, 
           type = 3,  
           box.palette = "RdBu", 
           shadow.col = "gray", 
           nn = TRUE,  
           cex = 0.5, 
           main = "First decision tree with X6")

predict_decisiontree_withX6 <- predict(dt_withX6, newdata = val_data,type = "class")

Fig 10. First decision tree with X6

The initial result from a decision tree with all default parameters was just a binary X6 node with two branches. I added some control parameters to be able to see further down the tree.

dt_withX6_control <- rpart(
  Pay.result ~ Credit.value + X2 + X3 + X4 + X5 + X6+  X7 + X8 + X9 + X11 + X12 + X13 + X14 + X15 + X16 + X17 + X18 + X19 + X20 + X21 + X22 + X23,
  data = train_data,
  method = "class", 
  control = rpart.control(
    cp = 0.001,        
    minsplit = 10,    
    maxdepth = 30     
  )
)

par(mar = c(5, 4, 4, 2) + 0.1)

rpart.plot(dt_withX6_control, 
           type = 3,  
           box.palette = "RdBu", 
           shadow.col = "gray", 
           nn = TRUE,  
           cex = 0.5, 
           main = "Second decision tree with X6")

predict_decisiontree_withX6_control <- predict(dt_withX6_control, newdata = val_data,type = "class")

Fig 11. Second decision tree with X6

The result was a tree so big that could not fit into the report properly without overlapping text and labels, regardless of the panel and text size. I noticed that X6 is at the top of three tree and therefore, I decided to do another tree without X6, to see the result.

decisiontree_noX6 <- rpart(
  Pay.result ~ Credit.value + X2 + X3 + X4 + X5 +  X7 + X8 + X9 + X11 + X12 + X13 + X14 + X15 + X16 + X17 + X18 + X19 + X20 + X21 + X22 + X23,
  data = train_data,
  method = "class"
  )

rpart.plot(decisiontree_noX6, 
           type = 3,  
           box.palette = "RdBu", 
           shadow.col = "gray", 
           nn = TRUE,  
           cex = 1, 
           main = "Third decision tree without X6 (all other variables)")

#predictions for basic decision tree
predict_decisiontree_noX6 <- predict(decisiontree_noX6, newdata = val_data,type = "class")

Fig 12. Third decision tree without X6

The decision tree without X6 was much smaller and it showed that X7, X11 and X18 are the variables most important without the dominant one. However it was still too big and computationally inefficient, therefore I pruned it using hyper parameters until it was readable and more computationally efficient.

I also created a confusion matrix for the pruned tree, once the model seemed to fit data well enough.

dt_pruned <- rpart(
  Pay.result ~ Credit.value + X2 + X3 + X4 + X5 + X6+  X7 + X8 + X9 + X11 + X12 + X13 + X14 + X15 + X16 + X17 + X18 + X19 + X20 + X21 + X22 + X23,
  data = train_data,
  method = "class",
  control = rpart.control(
    cp = 0.0001,        
    minsplit = 30,    
    maxdepth = 5     
  )
)

Decision tree grid search

As mentioned in the methodology, some of the models have grid searches to find the best fit or the best parameters. This grid search for decision trees has a max depth of 10 models and uses the bootstrap method.

#grid search 

paramGrid <- expand.grid(
  maxdepth=c(1:10)
)

train_control_dt <- trainControl(

Gradient boosting grid search

The gradient boosting grid search has a more extensive parameter grid list, including max depth, samples by tree, and nrounds. It uses the cross-validation method.

paramGrid_gbm2 <- expand.grid(nrounds = c(100,200),  
                              max_depth = c(10, 15, 20, 25),
                              colsample_bytree = seq(0.5, 0.9, length.out = 5),
                              eta = 0.1,
                              gamma=0,
                              min_child_weight = 1,
                              subsample = 1
)

train_control_gbm <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",  
  number = 10,      
  search = "grid"  
)

gbm2 <- train(Pay.result ~. , data = train_data, method = "xgbTree",
              tuneGrid = paramGrid_gbm2, trControl=train_control_gbm)

Data balancing

During the EDA I noticed that the data was unbalanced between classes, meaning that the Yes (majority class) had a lot more values than No (minority class). I decided at the end of the models, to perform data balancing and rerun the best two models in order to see if the accuracy, sensitivity and specificity can be further improved.

I chose to apply the oversampling method, often used for cases such as this one. It is defined by adding more copies to a minority class. Sometimes it is necessary to do data balancing, because some machine learning algorithms can be affected by a large disparity between the majority class and minority class and the fit of the model can suffer. The two classes do not need to be equal, but close in rows. (Vidhya, 2024)

The oversampling function include an N-desired which is represented by the number of samples you want to have in a balanced data set after the oversampling process, in this case 16000. Once the data is over sampled, it is stored into a new variable and label selection is performed.

After the pre-processing is done, I have applied the new data to the best KNN model.

Analysis and conclusion

This coursework uses confusion matrices, a performance measure for ML classifications, where the output is 2 or more classes (S., 2021). The specific output is a table of actual values and predicted values. It shows the number of predictions as a form of four:

  • True positive -> predicted correctly (top left)
  • True negative -> predicted correctly (bottom right)
  • False negative -> predicted wrong (bottom left)
  • False positive -> predicted wrong (top right), (S., 2021)

The confusion matrices also report the accuracy, sensitivity and specificity of a model, which is what this report has used to measure overall performance for comparison. Accuracy should always be high, ideally in the 90 range, however there will always be some sort of trade off between high accuracy and better sensitivity and specificity. Specificity is necessary because it measure the models ability to identify the negative instances. On the other hand, sensitivity measures the models ability to identify positive cases. (S., 2021)

In this report, the best models were represented by the kNN where k=3, as correctly predicted in Fig 5. Accuracy vs k value for kNN models where the best k was a low one. The second best model was the pruned decision tree. Both performed well enough on the never seen test data, however the clear winner is the kNN model. It achieved an overall accuracy of 97%, with sensitivity 99% and specificity of 89%. The pruned decision tree achieved an accuracy of 81%, with sensitivity 94% and specificity 34%. The kNN model has performed well on the test data, therefore there is no reason to suspect overfitting, even though a low k could mean the model has a chance of overfitting.

There is a probable reason why the kNN model achieved the best results, and that being that it used normalized train and validation set, which made the data smoother and much easier to compute. The decision tree, even if pruned, used non-normalized sets. Even though normalization is not typically required for decision trees, it might be worth investigating if normalized train and validation sets would perform better. Normalized sets passed through pruned trees can help with the overall interpretability of the model, a domain that needs further research.

In conclusion, this report has looked at the comparison between multiple classification models in order to help predict defaulters in credit card risk. Even though most models, including the grid searchers achieved almost the same accuracy, sensitivity and specificity, kNN has proved to be the successful models that could be further used in credit card risk assessment. Beyond that, the report used p value variable selection and feature importance for random forest, that showcased the X6 as the dominant variable overall.
